    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Ana de Armas All Movies List & Breakthrough Roles</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A comprehensive guide to her cinematic journey from Cuba to Hollywood</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Ana Celia de Armas Caso (born 30 April 1988) is a Cuban and Spanish actress who has rapidly ascended the ranks of Hollywood to become one of its most sought-after leading stars. She has been nominated for an Academy Award, a BAFTA, and two Golden Globes. Her filmography spans genres from romantic dramas and comedies to science fiction epics and high-octane action thrillers.</p>

      <h2>The Trajectory of a Global Star</h2>
      <p>Understanding an actor's filmography is like reading a map of their creative evolution. For Ana de Armas, this journey began in Cuba, shifted to Spain, and ultimately landed in Los Angeles. This progression mirrors a classic tech startup scaling globally—starting with a localized product (Spanish-language cinema), adapting for a new market (learning English for Hollywood), and eventually achieving "unicorn" status with leading roles in blockbuster franchises.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>The "Breakthrough" Formula:</strong> De Armas didn't just rely on standard leading-lady roles. Her strategic choice to play complex, sometimes morally ambiguous characters—like the AI Joi in <em>Blade Runner 2049</em> or the deceptively clever nurse Marta in <em>Knives Out</em>—served as the catalyst for her critical acclaim. She consistently leverages empathy and emotional intelligence as her primary acting tools, allowing her to stand out even in effects-heavy or ensemble casts.
      </div>

      <h2>Early Career: Cuba and Spain (2006–2014)</h2>
      <p>De Armas began her career in Cuba with a leading role in the romantic drama <em>Una rosa de Francia</em> (2006). Moving to Madrid, Spain, at the age of 18, she starred in the popular teen mystery drama <em>El Internado</em> (2007–2010), which gave her massive recognition in the Spanish-speaking world.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>Una rosa de Francia</em> (2006) - Marie</li>
        <li><em>Madrigal</em> (2007) - Stella Maris</li>
        <li><em>El edén perdido</em> (2007) - Gloria</li>
        <li><em>Mentiras y gordas</em> (2009) - Carola</li>
        <li><em>Faraday</em> (2013) - Inma Murillo</li>
        <li><em>Por un puñado de besos</em> (2014) - Sol</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Hollywood Transition (2015–2018)</h2>
      <p>Moving to Los Angeles required her to learn English phonetically for her early roles. This transition period was crucial, establishing her presence in American cinema alongside established stars.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>Knock Knock</em> (2015) - Bel (with Keanu Reeves)</li>
        <li><em>Exposed</em> (2016) - Isabel de la Cruz</li>
        <li><em>Hands of Stone</em> (2016) - Felicidad Iglesias</li>
        <li><em>War Dogs</em> (2016) - Iz</td>
        <li><em>Overdrive</em> (2017) - Stephanie</li>
        <li><em>Blade Runner 2049</em> (2017) - Joi (Breakthrough Role)</li>
        <li><em>Corazón</em> (2018) - Elena Ramírez</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Stardom and Critical Acclaim (2019–Present)</h2>
      <p>Following her breakout as Joi, de Armas secured roles that showcased her versatility, moving seamlessly between whodunits, spy thrillers, and intense biographical dramas.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>The Informer</em> (2019) - Sofia Koslow</li>
        <li><em>Wasp Network</em> (2019) - Ana Margarita Martínez</li>
        <li><em>Knives Out</em> (2019) - Marta Cabrera (Golden Globe nomination)</li>
        <li><em>Sergio</em> (2020) - Carolina Larriera</li>
        <li><em>The Night Clerk</em> (2020) - Andrea Rivera</li>
        <li><em>No Time to Die</em> (2021) - Paloma</li>
        <li><em>Deep Water</em> (2022) - Melinda Van Allen</li>
        <li><em>The Gray Man</em> (2022) - Dani Miranda</li>
        <li><em>Blonde</em> (2022) - Norma Jeane / Marilyn Monroe (Academy Award nomination)</li>
        <li><em>Ghosted</em> (2023) - Sadie Rhodes</li>
        <li><em>Eden</em> (2024) - TBA</li>
        <li><em>Ballerina</em> (2025) - Eve Macarro</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
      <p>The success of Ana de Armas is a significant data point in the evolving landscape of global cinema. She became the first Cuban woman nominated for the Academy Award for Best Actress for her role in <em>Blonde</em>. Her trajectory highlights the dismantling of traditional geographical and linguistic barriers in Hollywood, proving that talent from international markets can effectively pivot to become global box-office draws. Furthermore, her ability to anchor major action franchises—such as the <em>John Wick</em> spin-off <em>Ballerina</em>—demonstrates a shift towards more diverse casting in traditionally male-dominated genres, similar to how shows like <a href="/sites/siliconbased/the-terminal-list">The Terminal List</a> rely on strong ensemble dynamics to build out their cinematic universes.</p>

    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What was Ana de Armas's first English-speaking role?</summary>
        <p>Her first major English-speaking role was in the 2015 psychological thriller 'Knock Knock' alongside Keanu Reeves. She had to learn her lines phonetically as she was still learning English at the time.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is Ana de Armas in a James Bond movie?</summary>
        <p>Yes, Ana de Armas played Paloma, a highly capable CIA agent, in the 2021 James Bond film 'No Time to Die'. Despite limited screen time, her character was a fan favorite.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Did Ana de Armas play Marilyn Monroe?</summary>
        <p>Yes, she portrayed Marilyn Monroe in the 2022 biographical psychological drama 'Blonde'. Her performance was widely praised and earned her an Academy Award nomination for Best Actress.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is Ana de Armas in the John Wick franchise?</summary>
        <p>Yes, she leads the action thriller 'Ballerina' (2025), which is a spinoff installment set within the John Wick universe, expanding the lore of the assassin underworld.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What movie made Ana de Armas famous?</summary>
        <p>While she had earlier successes in Spain, her breakout role in Hollywood is widely considered to be the holographic AI Joi in 'Blade Runner 2049' (2017), followed closely by her Golden Globe-nominated performance as Marta Cabrera in the highly successful mystery film 'Knives Out' (2019).</p>
      </details>
    </section>
